            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mark Miller\u2019s life is measured in tolerances and tangible results. Raised in a quiet Portland suburb, he spent his youth in his father\u2019s garage, a machinist who taught him the profound satisfaction of shaping metal. While his friends were obsessed with video games, Mark was fascinated by the intricate mechanics behind the consoles. This hands-on upbringing instilled in him a preference for the physical world, a trait that would define his career.\n\nHe pursued a Bachelor's in Mechanical Engineering at Oregon State before being drawn to the epicenter of innovation, completing his graduate degree at Stanford. He arrived in Silicon Valley during the twilight of the dot-com boom, landing a job at a hardware startup that promised to revolutionize data storage. When the company spectacularly imploded a year later, Mark learned a crucial lesson: hype is fleeting, but solid manufacturing principles are timeless. He pivoted to more established firms, steadily climbing from design engineer to a leadership role.\n\nThe most significant turning point was his divorce five years ago. He and his ex-wife, a high-powered attorney, had built parallel, demanding careers that eventually diverged completely. The amicable split left Mark with a spacious Dogpatch loft and a profound sense of solitude. He poured his energy into his work, earning his Director title but realizing the corner office felt empty.\n\nToday, Mark\u2019s life runs with the precision of the Caltrain he rides daily. His 8.5-mile commute from the 22nd Street station to a sprawling manufacturing plant in South San Francisco is a ritual. The morning ride is for reviewing production schedules; the evening ride is for listening to history podcasts, a mental escape from the day\u2019s logistical challenges. He loves his Dogpatch neighborhood for its industrial bones and creative energy, a perfect reflection of his own personality.\n\nHis social life is small and loyal, consisting of a few colleagues and an old friend from Stanford. Weekends are a sanctuary of steel and leather, dedicated to meticulously restoring a 1978 BMW motorcycle in his building\u2019s shared workshop. His dream isn\u2019t to climb higher on the corporate ladder, but to one day open a small, high-end fabrication shop\u2014a return to the hands-on craft he learned in his father\u2019s garage. He hopes to finish the motorcycle by spring and take it on a solo trip up the coast, searching for a new gear in his own life."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was fourteen, standing in the garage that smelled of oil and metal shavings. His father\u2019s hand rested over his, guiding a cutting tool on the lathe for the first time. He remembers the low hum and the focused quiet. When they were done, a rough steel rod was transformed into a perfectly dimensioned pin, cool and smooth in his palm. It wasn't just about making a part; it was the moment he understood the profound, tangible magic of shaping the physical world. That feeling became his life\u2019s anchor.\n\n2.\nThe empty office in 2001 felt like a tomb. Just weeks before, it had buzzed with dot-com hype and promises of a digital revolution. Now, he watched movers haul out the servers\u2014the company\u2019s ghost in the machine. A whiteboard still held diagrams for a future that would never arrive. In that moment, the sheer physicality of failure was more real than any of the fleeting promises. He vowed then to build his career on things with weight and substance, things you could measure with a caliper.\n\n3.\nFive years ago, after the last moving box was loaded, he and his ex stood in their quiet, echoing living room. There was no anger, just a deep, tectonic split. \u201cBe good, Mark,\u201d she said, her voice gentle. The finality wasn't in her words, but in the soft click of the front door as she left. In the sudden, immense silence that followed, he felt the true shape of his solitude. He knew he had to rebuild his life from its foundation, just like any engineering project.\n\n4.\nLast Saturday night in the workshop, surrounded by the ghosts of old projects. He\u2019d spent months meticulously rewiring the BMW\u2019s engine. He turned the key, hit the starter, and after a stubborn cough, the engine roared to life. The raw, guttural sound vibrated through the concrete floor and up his arms, a jolt of pure mechanical life. It was more than noise; it was proof of resurrection. A belief that he, too, could bring a dormant part of his own soul back online.\n\n5.\nHe was on his evening Caltrain ride home a few months ago, the train rocking rhythmically past the industrial yards. His history podcast was on, but he wasn't hearing it. He watched the massive cranes silhouetted against the sunset and realized his Director title felt like a foreign language. The only thing that felt true was the memory of his father's garage. That was the moment his vague dream sharpened into a clear objective: he wasn\u2019t climbing a ladder, he was building a bridge back to himself."
